# Infrastructure Layer

Adapters that implement the ports declared by `domain`/`application`.
This is where frameworks and external systems live (Spring, JPA, HTTP clients, etc.).

## Structure

```
infrastructure/
├── persistence/   # JPA entities, repository impls, mappers (see persistence.mdc)
├── email/         # e.g. ResendEmailSender
├── security/      # e.g. JwtTokenGenerator, BCryptPasswordHasher
└── event/         # e.g. SpringEventPublisher
```

## Rules

- Each adapter **implements a port interface** from the inner layers. Name it by technology:
  `BCryptPasswordHasher implements PasswordHasher`, `ResendEmailSender implements EmailSender`.
- Adapters translate between the outside world and domain types — domain stays unaware of the tech.
- This is the only layer allowed to reference vendor SDKs / Spring infrastructure annotations
  (`@Repository`, `@Component`, config classes).
- Read secrets/config from Spring config (`@Value`/`@ConfigurationProperties`), never hardcode.

```java
// ✅ GOOD: infra implements a domain port using a vendor lib
@Component
public class BCryptPasswordHasher implements PasswordHasher {
    private final BCryptPasswordEncoder encoder = new BCryptPasswordEncoder();
    @Override public String hash(String raw) { return encoder.encode(raw); }
    @Override public boolean matches(String raw, String hashed) {
        return encoder.matches(raw, hashed);
    }
}
```

## Don't

- Don't put business rules here — only translation/integration.
- Don't let an adapter leak vendor types (e.g. a JPA entity, an SDK response) into
  `domain`/`application`. Map to domain types at the boundary.
